Meh. Similar to Fleur de Lys, or Sona in LA, it's ok food but without anything particularly notable, at least in the dishes we had. Nothing particularly challenging, or plain tasty-tasty. Ordered from the tasting side of the menu. I had some frog legs that were pretty so-so. To be fair, I don't know if Gary Danko was there that evening. Service was very good, though that night they were giving away some little amuse-bouche bundles at the end of a meal that nobody was particularly excited about. I think they held some rather bland muffin-type pasty. Seemed more like a token gesture than something they put real effort towards. Also, the decor is very dated. late 80s/early 90s hotelier. So if you're going for ambiance--and LOVE seashell/marble/decorative glassware, this is the place for you. Essentially, sophistication for spinster aunts. Get it better here: -Head of the class in this category for me is La Folie. The staff is fantastic, the chef is wonderful and extremely gracious, and the food is deftly handled. Plus they do a great champagne/caviar combination. Also if you are under 50, you will feel like a wild young thing. -Chez Papa is also very good, and much less expensive. Trendier, chic atmosphere.

Wow, this was not only a fantastic meal, it was a fantastic dining experience. Everyone who works here is extremely knowledgeable about specifics of each wine, each variety of cheese -- and everything in between. Plus they are extremely friendly and accommodating (for example, 4 or 5 couples asked them to snap a photo, most there are sommelier as well as waiters and will spend as long as you like talking about the subtleties of difference vintages. Now on to the food! I took my wife there for her birthday (apparently half the couples there did the same in our room of the restaurant). I can say this was the best meal I've had in several years. Really fantastic. Here's what we had: Appetizers * Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée * Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Apples Fish and Seafood * Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon * Seared Sea Scallops with Butternut Squash Purée, Apples, Caramelized Cauliflower and Tarragon Meat and Game Birds * Seared Filet of Beef with Leeks, Crimini Mushrooms, Braised Shallots and Potato Cake * Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Tian of Vegetables and Polenta Cheese A Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside Desserts Crème Fraîche Cheesecake with Cranberries and Caramelized Pecans

My husband, daughter and I dined on Tuesday March 1st for my husband's birthday. I was ready to be wowed by service and food and both fell short. We had very attentive service once we were seated and drink orders brought. In fact we were asked what we wanted to order before we had our drinks. It became fairly obvious that they wanted food order sooner rather than later!! So upon receiving our cocktails we perused and then ordered (after being asked three times). Didn't see a waiter again for over ten minutes, empty water glasses all around. My husband and I both ordered fois gras and it was enjoyable, though both of us agreed the caramelized onion was not as good an accompaniment as the apple. Next we had the crab and avocado salad, lacking spice and any pizzazz. My husband had the duck, great! My daughter had the ahi tuna, well cooked and beautiful flavours. I had the roast lobster, very small, no sides except some mashed potatoes which needed salt. We all had the cheese course. A wonderful array of cheeses from around the world. And the biggest disappointment was the fact they made no accommodation for our daughter being celiac,( no wheat, rye or barley). They just apologised when they brought the cheeses and said so we have some grapes. They Had no alternatives when they brought the bread at the beginning of the meal. I have dined at the Black Tree Restaurant (chef Matteo Paonessa ) in Burlington Ontario. Food spectacular, fois gras out of this world and he always has amazing options for gluten free people. Just saying. I wish I could say every bite was amazing but the evening was a disappointment for us.

The Short-Review: Superior service, a fun dining experience, tasty food. Met my expectations, but did not live up the hype or cost. The Long Review: APPETIZER Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Roasted Tomatoes, Corn and Peas (RECOMMENDED: Great texture, very flavorful, would eat 3 of them if I could) ENTREES - Braised Veal Breast with Pistachio Crusted Sweetbreads, Potato Purée, Leeks, Capers and Chanterelle Mushrooms (RECOMMENDED: Veal was buttery soft and had a nice savory taste to it. With over 2,000 reviews of Gary Danko, there's nothing I can add that hasn't been said already. However, I had to write a review simply to declare that Gary Danko is absolutely worthy of all the praise given here. First and foremost - the service was FANTASTIC. Every member of their staff, from the hostess to the busboys, was courteous, knowledgable, and genuinely friendly. Dining in LA, I frequently encounter arrogant, self-important restaurant staff, particularly at high-end establishments. There wasn't even a HINT of this pretentious nonsense at Gary Danko. Now the food... I will say, aside from the game meats we tried (sometimes adventurous foods aren't the best) everything was excellent. Our favorites of the evening: Amuse of Lobster Bisque - Fantastic... the first sip just exploded with fresh lobster flavor. The sweet and crunchy little bits of chopped onion were also an excellent complement. Butternut Squash Tart - Delicious crust that stayed crispy and a smooooth savory filling. I could have eaten a second one of these. The small lump of goat cheese mousse went a LONG way. Roast Maine Lobster - Perfectly cooked. Even the claw piece, which is hard to cook properly, was evenly tender all the way through. The mushrooms, buttery sauce, and potato puree were rich with their own unique flavors. Macaron ice cream sandwich - Seriously... one of the best desserts I've ever had, and I'm not one to care for dessert. The macrons were large, and they had the ideal consistency - crunchy shell, chewy centers. And the ice cream filings were so creamy and delcious *drooool* especially the Bailey's ice cream with caramel sauce. *DROOOOL* On top of this... the prices weren't bad and the portions were very generous compared to similar restaurants. Gary Danko: I will DEFINITELY come back again.

My sis and I made reservations 2 months in advance, and it was well worth the wait!! We were a party of 6, and it was the first time at the restaurant for all of us. The service is EXCELLENT, they all greeted us at the door and made us feel right at home. The restaurant is medium sized, and a little noisy, but well decorated and very clean. If food were the only factor, Gary Danko would be a solid 4 stars. Minus one star for service that left us disappointed. The menu setup is excellent. I love that you can choose the number of courses, choose multiple items from any group (ex: 2 appetizers instead of a fish course) then have them in any order (even dessert first if you want). The food was wonderful and every dish was beautifully plated with care. - Amuse Bouche of Gazpacho was not exactly bite-sized, but still beautiful and delicious - Risotto with Lobster was creamy and divine, except for the bite of shell in my dish - Bass w/Pesto was delicious, and the gnocchi underneath were like little pillows of heaven - Quail was impressive; it was deboned perfectly and the stuffing was delicious - Chocolate souffle was very flavorful, but mine was a bit too soupy I was pretty excited to finally experience Gary Danko and fully expected to do the full 5 courses. The problem was that the evening moved painstakingly slow. I can appreciate a long "experience" meal that lasts several hours, but not when it's a result of poor service. After we heard about the menu and ordered drinks our waiter disappeared. The evening continued with that theme. Between every course our empty plates sat for quite a long time, then when a back waiter would finally clear them it would be an additional long wait for the next course. Our bread and water was consistently refilled, but I was never offered a second glass of wine. Then between our 2nd and 3rd course our waiter apologized for a "mix-up" that caused an especially long delay and offered to send us a "snack". The 3rd course eventually appeared and the waiter explained that the snack would instead be a pre-dessert course. When our 3rd course plates were finally cleared we were tired and unwilling to continue with more waiting. We chose to cancel our cheese course (I was very disappointed) and had to inform a back waiter, as our waiter was again MIA. We eventually made it through 3 long dessert phases and during the final waiting period (this time for the check), I glanced around and noticed that other tables were waiting as well. A man at another table appeared to be dozing while his date was slumped over playing on her phone. Fine dining at this level should never result in that type of dining room behavior and it's unfortunate that the service left guests feeling this way. I like the idea of giving Gary Danko another try and wonder if the experience would be more positive with another server. The food is indeed very good, but I'm more likely to entrust my money and special occasion evening to a restaurant that won't let me down.

    My husband and I both ordered fois gras and it was enjoyable, though both of us agreed the caramelized onion was not as good an accompaniment as the apple. Next we had the crab and avocado salad, lacking spice and any pizzazz. My husband had the duck, great! My daughter had the ahi tuna, well cooked and beautiful flavours. I had the roast lobster, very small, no sides except some mashed potatoes which needed salt. We all had the cheese course. A wonderful array of cheeses from around the world.
    And the biggest disappointment was the fact they made no accommodation for our daughter being celiac,( no wheat, rye or barley). They just apologised when they brought the cheeses and said so we have some grapes. They Had no alternatives when they brought the bread at the beginning of the meal.
    I have dined at the Black Tree Restaurant (chef Matteo Paonessa ) in Burlington Ontario. Food spectacular, fois gras out of this world and he always has amazing options for gluten free people. Just saying.
    I wish I could say every bite was amazing but the evening was a disappointment for us.

    The Short-Review:
    Superior service, a fun dining experience, tasty food. Met my expectations, but did not live up the hype or cost. It would be a great location for a special occasion for those who have the cash, but don't expect to get crazy value for your money or the best dinner of your life at GD.

    The Long Review:

    APPETIZER
    Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Roasted Tomatoes, Corn and Peas
    (RECOMMENDED: Great texture, very flavorful, would eat 3 of them if I could)

    ENTREES -
    Braised Veal Breast with Pistachio Crusted Sweetbreads, Potato Purée, Leeks, Capers and Chanterelle Mushrooms
    (RECOMMENDED: Veal was buttery soft and had a nice savory taste to it. Definitely one of the most tender veal breasts I've had)

    Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Carrot-Ginger Purée and Cherries
    (Cooked well. The highlight would be the carrot-ginger puree, which means that the duck itself was good, but not out of this world)

    DESSERT
    Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Roasted Peaches, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream
    (An interesting dessert, but the texture is not for everyone. The peaches and compote were a great accent to the dish. Vanilla ice cream was... vanilla ice cream. A nice change-up for a dessert, but nothing utterly fantastic.)

    WINES
    2006 O'Connor (Russian River Valley) - Pinot Noir
    2007 Loring Wine Company (Chalone) - Pinot Noir

    Pros:
    + Friendly and professional service, as expected. Several waiters come by to serve your entree, fill your water, and update your cutlery on a frequent basis. They also have this verve about them that makes the food and experience that much more exciting.
    + Delicious food and a good number of options to choose from. Filling too (I got the four-course meal).
    + Fastest 3.5 hr dinner I've ever had. Time just flew by eating and having a wonderful time with my older brother and his friends.
    + A knowledgeable sommelier that provided great recommendations.
    + No mandatory 18% gratuity, a classy move here.
    + Decorative restrooms. You'll have to see it in person.

    Cons:
    - The layout of the restaurant is a little bit packed for my tastes. You could easily back into someone else if you were not sitting in one of their booths.
    - Food tasted great and it is everything you would expect. However, given all the great reviews and hype, I was expecting something a little bit more mind-blowing and unique from GD. The decor is pleasant on the eyes and the food is well-executed, but there wasn't anything that stood out in my mind at a restaurant of this calibur.
    - Food:Cost ratio could be a little better. My selections were delicious, but I still felt that the food wasn't completely worth the $85.

    1/25/2011

    With over 2,000 reviews of Gary Danko, there's nothing I can add that hasn't been said already. However, I had to write a review simply to declare that Gary Danko is absolutely worthy of all the praise given here.

    First and foremost - the service was FANTASTIC.  Every member of their staff, from the hostess to the busboys, was courteous, knowledgable, and genuinely friendly.  Dining in LA, I frequently encounter arrogant, self-important restaurant staff, particularly at high-end establishments.  There wasn't even a HINT of this pretentious nonsense at Gary Danko.

    Now the food... I will say, aside from the game meats we tried (sometimes adventurous foods aren't the best) everything was excellent.  Our favorites of the evening:

    Amuse of Lobster Bisque - Fantastic... the first sip just exploded with fresh lobster flavor.  The sweet and crunchy little bits of chopped onion were also an excellent complement.

    Butternut Squash Tart - Delicious crust that stayed crispy and a smooooth savory filling.  I could have eaten a second one of these.  The small lump of goat cheese mousse went a LONG way.

    Roast Maine Lobster - Perfectly cooked.  Even the claw piece, which is hard to cook properly, was evenly tender all the way through.  The mushrooms, buttery sauce, and potato puree were rich with their own unique flavors.

    Macaron ice cream sandwich - Seriously... one of the best desserts I've ever had, and I'm not one to care for dessert.  The macrons were large, and they had the ideal consistency - crunchy shell, chewy centers.  And the ice cream filings were so creamy and delcious *drooool* especially the Bailey's ice cream with caramel sauce.  *DROOOOL*

    On top of this... the prices weren't bad and the portions were very generous compared to similar restaurants.  Gary Danko:  I will DEFINITELY come back again.

    8/18/2013

    1 check-in

    If food were the only factor, Gary Danko would be a solid 4 stars.  Minus one star for service that left us disappointed.

    The menu setup is excellent.  I love that you can choose the number of courses, choose multiple items from any group (ex: 2 appetizers instead of a fish course) then have them in any order (even dessert first if you want).

    The food was wonderful and every dish was beautifully plated with care.

    - Amuse Bouche of Gazpacho was not exactly bite-sized, but still beautiful and delicious
    - Risotto with Lobster was creamy and divine, except for the bite of shell in my dish
    - Bass w/Pesto was delicious, and the gnocchi underneath were like little pillows of heaven
    - Quail was impressive; it was deboned perfectly and the stuffing was delicious
    - Chocolate souffle was very flavorful, but mine was a bit too soupy

    I was pretty excited to finally experience Gary Danko and fully expected to do the full 5 courses.  The problem was that the evening moved painstakingly slow.  I can appreciate a long "experience" meal that lasts several hours, but not when it's a result of poor service.  After we heard about the menu and ordered drinks our waiter disappeared.  The evening continued with that theme.  Between every course our empty plates sat for quite a long time, then when a back waiter would finally clear them it would be an additional long wait for the next course.  Our bread and water was consistently refilled, but I was never offered a second glass of wine.  Then between our 2nd and 3rd course our waiter apologized for a "mix-up" that caused an especially long delay and offered to send us a "snack".  The 3rd course eventually appeared and the waiter explained that the snack would instead be a pre-dessert course.  When our 3rd course plates were finally cleared we were tired and unwilling to continue with more waiting.  We chose to cancel our cheese course (I was very disappointed) and had to inform a back waiter, as our waiter was again MIA.  We eventually made it through 3 long dessert phases and during the final waiting period (this time for the check), I glanced around and noticed that other tables were waiting as well.  A man at another table appeared to be dozing while his date was slumped over playing on her phone.  Fine dining at this level should never result in that type of dining room behavior and it's unfortunate that the service left guests feeling this way.

    I like the idea of giving Gary Danko another try and wonder if the experience would be more positive with another server.  The food is indeed very good, but I'm more likely to entrust my money and special occasion evening to a restaurant that won't let me down.
